heading: BACKGROUND
content:
Plaintiffs own properties located in Franklin County, Virginia in the area around Boones Mill. MVP holds an easement to construct and maintain a natural gas pipeline across each of the properties. Recently, MVP began construction of the Mountain Valley Pipeline on Plaintiffs' properties. The Mountain Valley Pipeline is an approximately 300-mile-long pipeline running from Wetzel County, West Virginia to Pittsylvania County, Virginia. Construction of the pipeline is conditioned on, among other things, a permit from the Virginia State Water Control Board ("SWCB") pursuant to Section 401 of the Federal Clean Water Act. Under the Clean Water Act the SWCB must certify that construction and operation of the pipeline would not violate water quality standards. Moreover, the SWCB's permit made compliance with Virginia's erosion and sediment control statue and regulations a condition of the permit.
The first phase of construction of the pipeline requires MVP to clear a 125-foot right-of- way of all vegetation and remove the topsoil. These initial construction activities exposed a layer of reddish clay below the topsoil.
A steady rain began on May 15, 2018 and continued through May 19, dislodging large amounts of soil and mud from the denuded construction corridor. Soil and mud driven by rainwater runoff flowed down an exposed section of the easement on property adjacent to the Flora property. The soil and mud flowed across Cahas Mountain Road, which borders the Flora property, onto the Floras' hayfield and pasture and continued onto Little Creek, a stream that bisects the Floras' fields. The flow deposited soil and mud in the Floras' fields and in Little Creek. It also deposited about eight inches of mud on Cahas Mountain Road. Laurence Hammack, Construction halted at Mountain Valley Pipeline worksite following severe erosion in Franklin County, The Roanoke Times (May 20, 2018), http://www.roanoke.com/business/constr uction-halted-at-mountain-valley-pipeline-work-site-following-severe/article_2eeebd3a-5007- 56b0-9469-3e381b09b668.html.
Another rainstorm passed through the Boones Mill area on May 26 and 27. Rain on those days washed three to four inches of mud and soil from the denuded easements on to the Friths' and Hurts' shared private driveway. The rains also washed mud and soil onto the Frith and Hurt properties, some of which ended up in an unnamed tributary that runs across both of their properties.
Prior to the rain on May 15 through 19 and May 26 and 27, the Virginia Department of Environmental Quality ("DEQ") stated that erosion and sediment controls on the MVP right-of- way were installed properly but that after the rains on May 15 to 19 the erosion controls "disappeared." Laurence Hammack, Construction halted at Mountain Valley Pipeline worksite following severe erosion in Franklin County, The Roanoke Times (May 20, 2018), http://www.roanoke.com/business/construction-halted-at-mountain-valley-pipeline-work-site- following-severe/article_2eeebd3a-5007-56b0-9469-3e381b09b668.html. Prior to the May 15 to 19 rainstorm, Mr. Flora inspected the easement adjacent to his hayfield and observed that MVP had placed only a few "silt socks"1 and some concrete barriers on the easement to control erosion. Both the concrete barriers and the silt socks proved ineffective in holding back the runoff from the easement near the Flora property. In fact, Mr. Flora observed sediment-laden water running around the concrete barriers on the easement.
These same controls were used on the easements adjacent to the Frith and Hurt properties. Again, and during a much less intense rainstorm, these erosion controls failed to prevent mud from covering the shared private driveway and the Frith and Hurt properties.
DEQ has not required MVP to improve the erosion controls on MVP's easements since the rainstorms. DEQ levied no fines or penalties against MVP nor did it issue a formal stop-work order. DEQ has also not ordered MVP to reevaluate the use of certain erosion control mechanisms in light of their recent catastrophic failures and DEQ has not insisted that MVP use more stringent erosion control measures. Instead DEQ has publicly, and wrongly, stated that no sediment from the MVP easements reached any streams. But the eyewitness accounts of Plaintiffs, contemporaneous evidence recorded during the rainstorms, and DEQ internal emails show that sediment runoff into streams near MVP's easements was significant, widespread and nearly uncontrolled. An email from DEQ employee Elizabeth Abe to another DEQ employee Matthew Grant explains that while driving on Brick Church Road in Rocky Mount, Virginia she observed a stream so choked with mud from an MVP easement that water was not flowing through the stream. Ex. A. She also observed that MVP had failed to erect any erosion controls on its easement. Id.
For its part MVP has done little, if anything, to remedy the situation that led to large-scale mud deposition on Plaintiffs' properties. As of an inspection on May 28, 2018 MVP had not materially improved the erosion controls at any of the easements near Plaintiffs' properties. Silt fencing2 located on MVP easements near the Flora and Frith properties are riddled with holes and collapsing. Some of the ground underneath the silt fences has eroded away, leaving room for runoff to pass unimpeded underneath the fence. Silt socks on the same easements are only staked to the ground, not embedded in it, such that water may pass freely underneath them as well. Those areas also lack silt socks with enough height to prevent water from spilling over the top of them, especially where some already have mud built up on them. Proof of those conditions will be supported by testimony as to the personal observations of the Plaintiffs on their properties, as supported by photographs, videos, and water samples they took and/or collected. MVP constructed sediment dikes on some of the easements, but the dikes are not compacted and thus they themselves are susceptible to eroding away, completely nullifying their erosion prevention function. Moreover, the dikes are not seeded with grass mats, further adding to the likelihood that they will erode when it next rains. Silt socks placed in gaps in silt fencing and at the outlets of the dikes are secured only by stakes and are undermined by erosion in some places. The next significant rain will exploit the weaknesses in the erosion controls and lead to additional trespasses on Plaintiffs' properties. Neither DEQ nor MVP have addressed these weaknesses and trespasses will continue until MVP is enjoined to remedy those weaknesses.

heading: I. Likelihood of Success on the Merits
content:
Plaintiffs are likely to succeed the merits of their continuing trespass claim. MVP has shown that it has not been able to control the erosion and deposition of mud and soil from its easements onto Plaintiffs' properties, even during this early stage of construction. Even after its erosion controls failed on two separate occasions, MVP has not attempted to implement tighter controls or even fully repair the mediocre controls it has in place now. MVP's actions make it a near certainty that the next time there is a significant rain event, mud will erode from MVP's easements onto Plaintiffs' properties.
Virginia common law defines trespass as "an unauthorized entry onto property which results in interference with the property owner's possessory interests therein." Kurpiel v. Hicks, 731 S.E.2d 921, 925 (Va. 2012) (quoting Cooper v. Horn, 448 S.E.2d 403, 406 (Va. 1994)). That means "a plaintiff must prove an invasion that interfered with the right of exclusive possession of the land . . . that was a direct result of some act committed by the defendant." Id.  Plaintiffs here seek only the vindication of the golden rule of property law: "[t]he law requires that every person so use his own property as not to injure the property of another." Cooper v. Horn, 448 S.E.2d 403, 407 (Va. 1994).
The power to exclude is one of the most treasured strands in an owner's bundle of property rights. Loretto v. Teleprompter Manhattan CATV Corp., 458 U.S. 419, 435-36 (1982); Rakas v. Illinois, 439 U.S. 128, 143 (1978) ("One of the main rights attaching to property is the right to exclude others."). Violations of this right include trespass. Virginia recognizes the "general principle of law, [that] every person is entitled to the exclusive and peaceful enjoyment of his own land, and to redress if such enjoyment shall be wrongfully interrupted by another." Tate v. Ogg, 195 S.E. 496, 498 (Va. 1938).
Any physical entry upon the surface of the land constitutes such an invasion, whether the entry is "a walking upon it, flooding it with water, casting objects upon it, or otherwise." W. Page Keeton et al., Prosser and Keeton on the Law of Torts § 13, at 70 (5th ed. 1984). Cooper v. Horn, 248 Va. at 423. Proof of negligence is not necessary. Id. at 424.
The Virginia Supreme Court has recognized on multiple occasions that any physical invasion is sufficient to succeed on a trespass claim. Id. This is the case "whether the entry is a walking upon it, flooding it with water, casting objects upon it, or otherwise." Id. A continuing trespass is a trespass that is "committed by one against another [and] constantly repeated . . . ." Boerner v. McCallister, 89 S.E.2d 23, 25 (Va. 1955).
MVP has already committed a trespass against Plaintiffs property rights in their individual properties, and it is extremely likely the MVP will continue to trespass on Plaintiffs' properties when it rains. In fact, MVP has failed to implement erosion controls in a proper manner. MVP has failed to compact its sediment dikes and failed to seed them with grass. MVP also placed silt socks that are inadequate to absorb or redirect the mud-laden flow they receive. Additionally, MVP failed to repair holes in its erosion control mechanisms and erosion underneath those mechanisms and continues to use installation techniques that do not ensure the effectiveness of those controls. DEQ, although lax in its enforcement, is not charged with enforcing trespass law.4 It is, nevertheless, disheartening that DEQ stands idle while MVP refuses to implement effective erosion controls. Further, DEQ's public assessments of the scope of the erosion control failures are undercut by the observations of its own employees. DEQ has shown that by those and other actions that Plaintiffs cannot to rely on the Commonwealth to adequately protect their property rights. Plaintiffs are forced, therefore, to bring this action to ensure that their most fundamental property rights will be protected from MVP's failure to take the care and spend the money necessary to prevent its trespasses.
As a result of MVP's slipshod attempt at erosion control and the lack of a plan to remedy the past failures of the same controls currently in place, MVP is nearly certain to continue to deposit mud and soil from its easements onto Plaintiffs' properties when it rains, thus constituting a continuing trespass on Plaintiffs' properties.

heading: II. Imminent Irreparable Harm
content:
Absent an injunction Plaintiffs will suffer imminent and irreparable injury. MVP has been unable to prevent mud from being deposited on Plaintiffs' property and has taken few, if any, steps to prevent any future trespass on Plaintiffs' properties.
Violations of Plaintiffs' property rights constitute an irreparable injury under Virginia law. In holding that an injunction is the appropriate remedy for enforcement of real property rights, the Virginia Supreme Court explained that "the violation of a real property interest is deemed irreparable and the owner protected in the enjoyment of his property whether such be sentimental or pecuniary." Norfolk S. Ry. v. Breeden, 756 S.E.2d 420, 424-25 (Va. 2014) (quoting Levisa Coal Co. v. Consolidation Coal Co., 662 S.E.2d 44, 54 (Va. 2008)). In the case of a continuing trespass, as Plaintiffs claim here, the Defendant's were in compliance with DEQ's requirements, which it is not, such compliance would not affect its duty to also comply with its common law obligations.
continuing trespass may be enjoined even though each individual act of trespass is in itself trivial, or the damage is trifling, nominal or insubstantial, and despite the fact that no single trespass causes irreparable injury. The injury is deemed irreparable and the owner protected in the enjoyment of his property whether such be sentimental or pecuniary.
Levisa Coal, 662 S.E.2d at 54 (quoting Boerner, 89 S.E.2d at 25). This is so because "where an injury by one against another is being constantly repeated, so that the complainant's remedy at law requires the bringing of successive actions, the legal remedy is inadequate, and the trespass will be prevented in equity by an injunction, the prevention of a multiplicity of actions at law being one of the special grounds of equity jurisdiction." Boerner, 89 S.E.2d at 25. MVP's lack of effective erosion controls will likely result in future injuries to Plaintiffs' properties each time an appreciable amount of rain falls. Accordingly, Plaintiffs' injuries can only be remedied by an injunction barring future trespasses by MVP.

heading: III. Balance of the Harms
content:
The balance of harms in this case tips decidedly in favor of Plaintiffs.5 Plaintiffs have suffered and will continue to suffer violations of their property rights until MVP remedies its ineffective erosion controls. MVP's will suffer no harm whatsoever.
MVP has violated and will continue to violate Plaintiffs' most fundamental property right: the right of exclusion. "The explanation for the pervasive nature of the institution of [property rights] lies in the fundamental need, apparent across time and cultures, to separate me from thee." Richard Epstein, Property as a Fundamental Civil Right, 29 Cal. W. Law Rev. 187, 188 (1992). It does Plaintiffs grievous harm for MVP to continue to infringe on this most basic of rights.
By contrast, MVP "will suffer no harm by being enjoined from doing what the law already prohibits." Solis v. Manalapan Mining Co., No. 10-115-GFVT, 2010 WL 2197534, at *6 (E.D. Ky. May 27, 2010). An injunction here would prevent MVP from trespassing on Plaintiffs' properties by requiring more stringent erosion controls. MVP is already barred from trespassing on property to which it has no rights. As a result, MVP "can claim little or no harm from being ordered to simply comply with existing . . . law . . . ." Dunbar v. Landis Plastics, Inc., 996 F. Supp. 174, 181 (S.D.N.Y. 1998); see also Audi AG v. D'Amato, 469 F.3d 534, 550 (6th Cir. 2006) ("In balancing the hardships between each party, we note that D'Amato faces no hardship in refraining from willful trademark infringement . . . ."); Warner Bros. Entm't, Inc. v. Vega, No. 11- 05895(SPx), 2012 WL 13008442, at *4 (C.D. Cal. Mar. 29, 2012) ("While Plaintiff will be harmed by continuing infringement, there appears to be no harm to Defendants . . . because an injunction would merely require Defendants to comply with the Copyright Act."); Microsoft Corp. v. McGee, 490 F. Supp. 2d 874, 883 (S.D. Ohio 2007).
Measured against the harm to Plaintiffs' foundational property rights, MVP can lay no claim to any harm over and above the "harm" of complying with Virginia law. To argue otherwise would permit MVP to realize benefits from reduced costs of construction by transferring its costs onto Plaintiffs. Consequently, while Plaintiffs have suffered and will continue to suffer violations of their fundamental property rights without an injunction, MVP will merely suffer compliance with the law.

heading: IV. The Public Interest
content: The public interest lies in protecting the property rights of Plaintiffs from continuing trespass by MVP. The right of exclusion and its necessary corollary, the enforcement of trespass by American courts. On the other hand, it would violate the public interest to allow MVP to push its costs of business onto innocent landowners throughout Virginia who are too often the unwilling neighbors of a bully set on trampling basic property rights for its private, and illegitimate gain. In short, MVP should not be allowed to increase its profits by illegally harming and trespassing on others' property.

heading: ARGUMENT
content: The standard for granting injunctive relief requires a moving party to establish:  (1) A substantial likelihood of success on the merits; (2) irreparable harm if an injunction is not granted; (3) the necessity of the injunction outweighs the harm to the Defendant, and (4) the issuance of the injunction will not be adverse to the public interest.  Direx Israel, Ltd. v. Breakthrough Medical Corp., 952 F.2d 802 (4th Cir. 1992).  The two most important factors are the probable irreparable harm to the moving party if an injunction is not issued, and the probable harm to the non-moving party if an injunction is issued.  Rockford Mfg., Ltd. v. Bennet, 296 F.2d 681 (D.S.C. 2003) (citing Blackwelder Furniture Co. v. Selig Mfg. Co., Inc., 550 F.2d 189 (4th Cir. 1977).  South Carolina courts generally afford a litigant temporary injunctive relief when reasonably necessary to protect a litigant's legal rights pending the judicial resolution of the facts at issue. Peek v. Spartanburg Reg.'l Healthcare Sys., 367 S.C. 450, 626 S.E. 34 (2005).  Once a prima facie demonstration has been made entitling a plaintiff to temporary injunctive relief, a restraining or preliminary injunction will be granted without regard to the ultimate determination of the case on the merits.  Helsel v. City of North Myrtle Beach, 307 S.C. 29, 430 S.E.2d 824 (1992).

heading: I. PLAINTIFFS WILL SUFFER IRREPARABLE HARM IF RELIEF IS NOT GRANTED.
content:
Plaintiffs will suffer irreparable harm in the event that construction is completed in violation of the Declaration.  In the event that the building is completed, it will permanently obstruct the visibility of the Ingles stores from adjacent roads, and in particular, the center view corridor.  This obstruction will irreparably damage Ingles by interfering with the visibility of its store, which is of paramount importance to Ingles when deciding to locate and site a grocery store.  Moreover, pursuant to the terms of the Lease, the development of Parcels 2 and 3 in a manner inconsistent with the Declaration could result in a default by Sky King under the Lease, and such development will forever materially affect Sky King's rights with regard to the development of the shopping center.
Interests in the real property are unique and thus the deprivation of such interests causes irreparable harm, and real property includes leasehold interests.  Recently, the Court of Appeals cited to a discussion in a federal First Circuit Court of Appeals decision on the irreparable harm suffered by a lessee:
Real estate has long been thought unique, and thus, injuries to real estate interests frequently come within the ken of the chancellor.  Then, too, harm to goodwill, like harm to reputation, is the type of harm not readily measurable or fully compensable in damages - and for that reason, more likely to be found "irreparable." ... Beyond goodwill, the loss of revenues, resulting from consideration such as diminished visibility, restricted access, less commodious parking, and the like or sufficiently problematic as to defy precise dollar quantification.
Kmart Corp. v. Oriental Plaza, Inc., 875 F.2d 907, 915 (1st Cir. 1989) (cited in H.H.Hunt Corp. v. Town of Lexington, 389 S.C. 623, 699 S.E.2d 699 (Ct. App. 2010) (finding that a restriction on the use of a party's property makes it unlikely that money damages will provide an adequate remedy).
Temporary relief is "used to preserve the subject of controversy in the condition which it is at the time of the order until opportunity is offered for full and deliberate investigation." Mailsource, 356 S.C. at 368, 588 S.E.2d at 638.  With respect to demonstrating the inadequacies of Plaintiffs' legal remedies, the Court's decision in Peek is instructive.  In determining that potential legal remedies would be inadequate, the Court in Peek relief upon the fact that the plaintiff's business "would be long loss before her claims against the [defendant] were adjudicated."  367 S.C. at 457, 626 S.E.2d at 38.
Similarly, the harm that will result to Plaintiffs from the continued construction of the building will be immediate and substantial.  Even ultimate success on the merits may prove a little more than a hollow victory, unless a court requires the building to be destroyed.  While a court may award monetary damages for loss of profits, in most cases however, "injunctive relief is a better remedy because it allows for continuation of the business operations pending a final adjudication on the merits.  Id. (emphasis added) (holding that temporary injunctive relief was a more appropriate remedy because it permitted the plaintiff to retain her customer base and continued to receive income from the business).  Real property is a unique interest as no two properties are alike, or to such interest is not readily measurable or fully compensable in damages.  See Kmart Corp. v. Oriental Plaza, Inc., supra.
Absent intervention from this Court, construction of the building will permanently and materially obstruct the view of the Ingles store from adjacent roads and affect Sky King's rights under the Lease and future development of the shopping center.  As a result, Plaintiffs' careful planning regarding the location access and view of the Ingles store and other improvements in the shopping center will all be for naught.  Plaintiffs will not be able to maintain the center view site line, which is of major importance to it in selecting a building site for Ingles and most other potential future tenants. Furthermore, Plaintiffs will not benefit from its careful planning and having restrictions placed on the property so as to not impede the view of the Ingles store, which it bargained for but will not receive.  The obstruction will impair the value of its store, its ability to attract new customers, and the value of the premises under future leases for the space.  These injuries satisfy application of the irreparable harm standard.  It is essential, therefore, that the Court enjoin Defendants from continuing construction on the building to obstruct the view of the Ingles store, and which is in contravention of the restrictive covenants, which were placed on the property by virtue of, inter alia, the Declaration.

heading: II. DEFENDANTS WILL SUFFER NO SUBSTANTIAL HARM.
content: In contrast to the harm that will be suffered by Plaintiffs if construction is not halted pending resolution of this matter, no substantial harm will befall the Defendants.  Bill Akkry is presently a tenant in the shopping center.  He operates a pizza parlor and a liquor center.  He has been operating these businesses since 2001 and continues to do so.  Upon information and belief, the building being constructed by Maria will house the pizza parlor, as well as the liquor store. Akkry continues to operate those businesses in the shopping center, receiving income therefrom during the pendency of this litigation. Thus, the cessation of construction pending a resolution of this matter will pose little or no hardship on the Akkrys. Moreover, as set forth below, Defendants were on notice of the development restrictions on the property before beginning construction, and opted to proceed at their peril.

heading: III. PLAINTIFFS WILL LIKELY PREVAIL ON THE MERITS.
content:
When seeking temporary injunctive relief under South Carolina law, "the plaintiff need not prove an absolute legal right; the plaintiff need only present a fair question to raise as to the existence of such a right."  Williams v. Jones, 92 S.C. 342, 347, 75 S.E. 705, 710 (1912). Therefore, "the determination of whether to grant an injunction should not be based on the merits of the underlying case except insofar as the merits may assist the trial court in determining whether a prima facie showing has been made."  Peek v. Spartanburg Reg'l Healthcare Sys., 367 S.C. 450, 456, 626 S.E.2d at 37 (citing Mailsource, LLC v. M.A. Bailey & Assocs., 356 S.C. 363, 368, 588 S.E.2d 635, 638 (Ct. App. 2003)).
"[A]s voluntary contracts, restrictive covenants will be enforced unless they are indefinite or contravene public policy."  Seabrook Island Property Owners Ass'n v. Marshland Trust, Inc., 358 S.C. 655, 661, 596 S.E.2d 380, 383 (2004) (quoting Houck v. Rivers, 316 S.C. 414, 416, 450 S.E.2d 106, 108 (Ct. App. 1994).  Prior to beginning construction, Maria was on notice that it could not construct one building on the two parcels it purportedly owns.  The Declaration of Reciprocal Easement, filed in the RMC Office on June 10, 2002, provides as follows:
5.3 Restrictions Relating to Development. Development and use restrictions shall limit the construction to be performed on Parcels 1, 2, and 3 to the construction of one building of one story and no more than twenty-four (24) feet in height in the locations and with the requisite parking spaces, shown on "Exhibit E" attached hereto.
Thus, the Declaration by its terms limits construction on Parcels 1, 2, or 3 to one building per parcel. Defendant Maria purportedly owns only Parcels 2 and 3; therefore, any argument that this restriction contemplated one building on multiple parcels is inapposite. Such a construction would make development of Parcel 1, which is not contiguous with Parcels 2 and 3, completely impossible. In addition, Restriction 5.3 references an attached "Exhibit E."  Exhibit E (which allegedly was not attached to the filed document) clearly delineates the fact that the Declarationlimits development of Parcels 1, 2, or 3 to one building per parcel, and sets forth the location of each potential building.  Even if the exhibit was not attached to the Declaration, Defendant Maria was on notice to inquire about Exhibit E's contents.
In the context of a real estate transaction, constructive or inquiry notice arises when a party becomes aware or should have become aware of certain facts, which, if investigated, will reveal the claim of another.  A party will be charged by operation of law with all knowledge that an investigation by a reasonably cautious and prudent purchaser would have revealed.  Spence v. Spence, 368 S.C. 106, 828 S.E.2d 869 (2008).  Here, the Declaration was a matter of public record.  The Declaration specifically indicated there were restrictions as to construction on Parcels 1, 2, and 3 and referenced a specific exhibit.  "[A] purchaser cannot carelessly disregard record notice of potential encumbrances, even when the adequacy of notice is questionable." South Carolina Tax Commission v. Belk, 266 S.C. 539, 544, 225 S.E.2d 177, 180 (1976).  A prudent purchaser would have made further inquiry as to the contents of Exhibit E.  Exhibit E, which is a depiction of Parcels 1, 2, and 3 taken directly from the approved site plan attached to the amendment to the Lease, shows clearly that a building spanning more than one lot is not allowed.  Thus, Defendant is charged with this knowledge, which one simple inquiry would have revealed.
Moreover, Defendant had knowledge of the Declaration before construction began, as its counsel was furnished a copy of the Declaration, as well as Exhibit E by counsel for Plaintiffs.

heading: IV. PUBLIC INTEREST FAVORS GRANTING AN INJUNCTION.
content: As set forth above, restrictive covenants are contracts, which Courts enforce.  Plaintiffs took substantial pains to assure the sightlines to its grocery store would be protected, along with their other interests in the lease and the shopping center.  Failure to protect Plaintiffs' interests, recognized by South Carolina law, would not favor the public interest.

heading: A. AN ARBITRATION AGREEMENT EXISTS AND MUST BE ENFORCED PER THE TERMS OF THE DEALERSHIP AGREEMENT.
content:
As noted, the Dealership Agreement demonstrates a clear agreement to submit "any dispute," and "all disputes...concerning the subject matter" of the Dealership Agreement to "binding arbitration conducted in Atlanta, Georgia."  Exhibit A at § 18.  The language of the arbitration agreement is clear and unequivocal.
Plaintiff alleges that it is entitled to the rights and remedies under the Dealership Agreement and, indeed, all of the counts in its complaint are fundamentally predicated on the relationship created by the Dealership Agreement.  Complaint at Counts I - III.  Given that reality, and the fact that certain of JCB‟s defenses to Plaintiff‟s allegations arise out of the Dealership Agreement, these disputes are subject to arbitration as provided in the Dealership Agreement.  Therefore, this Court should recognize the arbitration agreement and enforce arbitration per the terms of the Agreement.

heading: B. THE ARBITRATION AGREEMENT IS ENFORCEABLE UNDER BOTH MAINE AND FEDERAL LAW.
content:
That conclusion is one which is both militated by the terms of the Dealership Agreement, and pursuant to the Federal Arbitration Act (FAA).
The FAA provides:
A written provision in . . . a contract evidencing a transaction involving commerce to settle by arbitration a controversy thereafter arising out of such contract or transaction, or the refusal to perform the whole or any part thereof, or an agreement in writing to submit to arbitration an existing controversy arising out of such a contract, transaction, or refusal, shall be valid, irrevocable, and enforceable, save upon such grounds as exist at law or in equity for the revocation of any contract.
9 U.S.C.A. § 2.  The FAA was designed "‟to overrule the judiciary‟s longstanding refusal to enforce agreements to arbitrate.‟"  Bradley v. Harris Research Inc., 275 F.3d 884, 888 (9th Cir. 2001) (citing Volt Info. Scis., Inc. v. Bd. of Trs. of the Leland Stanford Jr. Univ., 489 U.S. 468, 474 (1989), quoting Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. v. Byrd, 470 U.S. 213, 219-20 (1985)). Congressional passage of the FAA "was motivated first and foremost by a congressional desire to enforce agreements into which parties had entered."  Dean Witter Reynolds, 470 U.S. at 220.  "It simply requires courts to enforce privately negotiated agreements to arbitrate, like other contracts, in accordance with their terms."  Volt, 489 U.S. at 478.  Accordingly, this Court should enforce the arbitration provisions of the Dealership Agreement, and either dismiss this action or stay this proceeding pending the outcome of the required arbitration.
Moreover, assuming, without conceding, that Maine law applies to this dispute, that conclusion is consistent with Maine‟s Uniform Arbitration Act, which provides that a written contract to submit to arbitration is "valid, enforceable and irrevocable, save upon such grounds as exist in law or in equity for the revocation of any contract."  14 M.R.S. § 5927.  Because Plaintiff here has never alleged that the Dealership Agreement should be revoked-and, indeed, predicates its claims on the existence of the Dealership Agreement-there is no basis under the Maine Uniform Arbitration Act for not enforcing the parties‟ arbitration agreement.  See generally V.I.P., Inc. v. First Tree Dev. Let. Liab. Co., 770 A.2d 95 (Me. 2001) (noting Maine‟s "broad presumption" favoring arbitrability, such that Maine courts will find disputes arbitrable "unless it may be said with positive assurances that the arbitration clause is not susceptible of an interpretation that governs the asserted dispute.  Doubts should be resolved in favor of arbitration").
Moreover, any argument by Plaintiff that Maine law precludes enforcement of the Dealership Agreement‟s arbitration clause is foreclosed by Federal preemption principles.  The FAA does not contain any express preemption provisions and does not indicate a congressional intent to occupy the entire field of arbitration.  Volt, 489 U.S. at 477.  "But even when Congress has not completely displaced state regulation in any area, state law may nonetheless be pre- empted to the extent that it actually conflicts with federal law - that is, to the extent that it „stands as an obstacle to the full accomplishment and execution of the full purposes and objectives of Congress.‟"  Id. (quoting Hines v. Davidowitz, 312 U.S. 52, 67 (1941).  Accordingly, any state- law based argument by Plaintiff to avoid the Dealership Agreement‟s arbitration clause is preempted by Federal law, and should be summarily rejected by the Court.

heading: III. SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
content:
The Plaintiff alleges violations of the Fourth and First Amendments by Officer Brandreth, and potentially (although it is ambiguous) a violation of Equal Protection guarantees.
There is no case that established, at the time the plaintiff received the ticket,that preventing someone from causing traffic to stop at a green light thereby causing a traffic hazard somehow violated a party's First Amendment rights, and therefore qualified immunity would apply.
The Plaintiff alleges that Officer Brandreth violated the Plaintiff's Fourth Amendment rights to be free of unlawful searches or seizures by giving her a summons to appear in court for violating RSA 644:2(II)(c).  However, the Plaintiff does not allege that Officer Brandreth unreasonably prolonged the alleged seizure beyond the time reasonably required to complete "the mission" and therefore there was no violation of the Fourth Amendment.  Further, Officer Brandreth had probable cause to issue Ms. Petrello a summons, and this is an alternative reason why there was no violation of the Fourth Amendment.  Finally, Officer Brandreth is entitled to qualified immunity from the Fourth Amendment claim as probable cause was at least arguable, particularly where Officer Brandreth was following the recommendation of his superiors.
Officer Brandreth did not violate Ms. Petrello's First Amendment rights.  She was not prohibited from showing her sign to persons traveling on the road.  The charge came when she caused a vehicle to stop with a green light, thereby causing a traffic hazard.  That was a violation under a reasonable interpretation of the statute, and was a reasonable time, place and manner restriction on the Plaintiff's First Amendment rights, was content neutral, and did not impair her from conveying any message that she wished to convey.
To the extent that the Plaintiff intended to plead a claim for violation of Equal Protection as to Officer Bandreth, the plaintiff has failed to state a claim, as the driver of the Cadillac and the Plaintiff were not similarly situated.

heading: A.  Officer Brandreth is entitled to qualified immunity based on the allegations in the Plaintiff's Complaint.
content:
The doctrine of qualified immunity provides that public officials have immunity from suit and is not a mere defense to liability. Maldonado v. Fontanes, 568 F.3d 263 (1st Cir. 2009).
Qualified immunity protects public officials against §1983 liability so long as they acted reasonably. Hunter v. Bryant, 502 U.S. 224, 228 (1991).  As the Supreme Court has said, qualified immunity provides ample protection to all but the plainly incompetent or those who normally violate the law. Malley v. Briggs, 475 U.S. 335, 341 (1986).  The aim is to protect those who might otherwise be deterred from official duties for fear that an innocent mistake would create personal liability. Joyce v. Town of Tewksbury, 112 F.3d 19, 23 (1st Cir. 1997). . The protection of qualified immunity applies regardless of whether the government officials' error is a mistake of law, a mistake of fact, or a mistake based on mixed questions of law and fact. Pearson v. Callahan, 555 U.S. 223 (2009).
Ordinarily, qualified immunity inquiry is a two part test.  A court must decide:  (1) whether the facts alleged or shown by the Plaintiff make up a violation of a constitutional right, and (2) if so, whether the right was clearly established at the time of the Defendant's alleged violation. Maldonado, 568 F.3d at 269.
The Court's typical approach is to first determine whether there was a constitutional right violated, and then secondly, determine whether that right was clearly established under the law. Pearson, 555 U.S. at 232.  However, in Pearson, the Supreme Court recognized that in many cases it would be more useful to first determine whether the right was clearly established at all so that courts could avoid attempting to make uncertain assumptions about state law. Id. at 238. Determining whether the law is clearly established follows the Court's general policy preference to avoid passing on a constitutional question if there is also present some other ground upon which the case may be disposed of. Id. at 241.  The Court noted that there will be cases in which a court will rather quickly and easily decide that there was no violation of clearly established law before having to turn to the more difficult question of whether the relevant facts make out a constitutional question at all. Id. at 239-240.  The Defendants assert that this is one of those cases where the law is not clearly established, and that issue should be decided first.

heading: 1. Officer Brandreth's actions did not violate clearly established law of which a reasonable officer would have been aware of.
content:
Under the second part of the qualified immunity test, Officer Brandreth did not violate clearly established law.  In order to prevail on this part of the test, the Plaintiff would have to show that RSA 644:2(II)(c) had previously been interpreted in this jurisdiction (or at the least that a similar statute was interpreted by a court that controls this jurisdiction, i.e., the First Circuit) that a situation where an individual successfully causing moving traffic to stop against a green light, thereby causing an obstruction to traffic behind it, did not fall within the meaning of this statute.  Absent such a finding, it cannot be said that there is any clearly established law that holds Officer Brandreth's interpretation of the statute was unreasonable.  Accordingly, the Plaintiff's proposition-that RSA 644:2(II)(c) does not apply to a person who attempts and succeeds in getting traffic to stop against a green traffic light and then physically interacts with the driver--is not clearly established.
There is an obvious public safety interest in curtailing this specific activity, where the Plaintiff has caused a vehicle to stop against the prevailing traffic pattern. Obviously, this could cause a traffic accident where the vehicles behind would note the green light and assume the vehicle in front of them was going to proceed uninterrupted, and could also cause an accident by the vehicle behind becoming frustrated in trying to make the light and pulling out into a lane where another vehicle could come upon it.  This is an obvious, reasonable exercise of the municipal police power.  The court can take judicial notice of the time and expense that municipalities spend on traffic patterns, traffic lights and that the State has established substantial "rules of the road" to promote traffic flow. See for example, note the "Traffic Control Standards, Statutes & Policies" (TCSSP), used to determine where traffic lights are necessary. Bergeron v. City of Manchester, 140 N.H. 417, 419, (1995).
The Plaintiff attached to her Complaint as Exhibit A documents from the Manchester Police Department pursuant to a Right-to-Know law request. Within those documents at page 37 of the Exhibit is an email from Captain James Soucy of the Community Policing Division to all Officers with the subject "Panhandlers." One section of the email advises officers as follows:
"Simply put, if a panhandler does any of the following - you may use these options:
Action: Panhandler causes traffic to slow or become impeded when accepting donations -even if they are not standing or step into a public way. Officer's Option: Charge with DOC 644:2 (c) Obstructing vehicular traffic in any public street."
Based on Plaintiff's allegations and the documents attached to Plaintiff's Complaint, Officer Brandreth was instructed to use this statute as one way of controlling the interaction between panhandlers and moving vehicles. A reasonable police officer in his place who had received such an instruction from his superior officers has an additional reason to believe that there was no clearly established law that prohibited using this statute to curtail interaction between pedestrians and motor vehicles, such as that between Ms. Petrello and the Cadillac which had the green light on the day in question.
The Plaintiff's argument seems to be that she had to have her feet planted in the roadway to be obstructing traffic, although there is no dispute that she reached out into the roadway to physically interact with a vehicle. One can think of several scenarios where an individual could be charged under the statute, for example, a person brandishing a toy gun to try to cause a car to stop, pretending to be injured by the side of the road, and other actions which does not require the person to actually step out into the road. There is no language in the statute that requires that a subject's feet must actually be planted in the road, and there is certainly no case law that establishes that interpretation. Under this very specific factual scenario-the Plaintiff physically interacting with moving traffic and causing a vehicle to stop against a green light-there is no clearly established law to say that Officer Brandreth's enforcement of the statute in these circumstances violated clearly established law.

heading: 2.  Plaintiff's First Amendment Claim.
content: Officer Brandreth's actions in ticketing the Plaintiff under the state statute based on the specific facts which he observed meant that the statute was applied in a content neutral manner. There are no allegations in the Complaint that this action was taken because of the specific speech that Ms. Petrello was attempting to convey on the day in question (i.e., she had some sort of a poster with words written on it and there is no allegation that she was being sanctioned because of whatever the content was on that poster).  When a law restricts speech without regard to the type of message communicated, and only regulates the time, place or manner of speech, then the ordinance is what is called "content neutral."  Such a law has the virtue of not singling out any idea or topic for favored or unfavored treatment.  The government must only show that a restriction that is content neutral is narrowly tailored to serve significant governmental interests and that it would leave ample alternative channels for communication of the information. Cutting v. City of Portland, 802 F.3d 79, 84 (1st Cir. 2015). Ms. Petrello was not prohibited in any way from expressing herself adjacent to the sidewalk as much as she desired, and there is no allegation in the Complaint that there was any attempt to restrict this. Based on the allegations in the Complaint, it is undisputed that what was restricted by application of the statute, and under the specific factual circumstances of this case, was the Plaintiff's interaction with a several ton automobile which was traveling with a green light, which caused the vehicle to stop and thereby caused a traffic hazard. Enforcement of that statute under those specific facts was a reasonable time, place and manner restriction that did not violate the First Amendment.

heading: a. Qualified immunity and the First Amendment.
content: The Plaintiff's right to attempt to stop moving traffic that has a green light to reach into the roadway and take items from the driver is not a clearly established right under the First Amendment. Cutting v. City of Portland, supra, is inapposite. In Cutting, the city of Portland, Maine banned all persons from standing on all traffic islands in the city. The court found that although the ordinance was content neutral, it was not narrowly tailored to limit its effects on free speech and was therefore found unconstitutional. Here, the plaintiff was free to maintain her position and convey her message to passing motorists. She was ticketed under a very narrow set of facts i.e. physically interacting with a motor vehicle which had the green light and causing it to stop against a green light. At the least, such a reasonable interpretation of the statute would not put a reasonable police officer on notice that he was violating the Plaintiff's First Amendment rights, and qualified immunity should apply to this claim as to the individual officer.

heading: B.  Plaintiff's Equal Protection Claims.
content:
The Plaintiff fails to state a claim for a violation of Plaintiff's equal protection rights under the Constitution.  Count III contains Plaintiff's claim of "violation of the Fourteenth Amendment's Equal Protection Clause."  A careful reading of that count which runs from paragraph 98 to paragraph 113 nowhere mentions or describes Officer Brandreth.  Although it is said to be "against all Defendants" it appears only to describe the development of a municipal policy to use RSA 644:2(II)(c), and otherwise complains about failure of training, etc. In fact in paragraph 110 it alleges, "the City of Manchester failed to train its police officers about the First Amendment right of individuals to peacefully panhandle in public places adjacent to roadways and how to properly apply RSA 644:2(II)(c) thereby permitting Officer Brandreth to be in a position to selectively and in a discriminatory fashion violate Ms. Petrello's constitutional rights." As discussed above, Officer Brandreth was following department policy (See Exh. A to the Complaint, p. 37.)
The Federal and State Equal Protection Clauses do not "demand that a statute necessarily apply equally to all persons or require things which are different in fact to be treated in law as though they were the same." Michael M. v. Sonoma County Superior Court, 450 U.S. 464, 469, (1981). Where a classification "realistically reflects the fact that the [two groups] are not similarly situated in certain circumstances," id., and the legislation's differing treatment of the groups is sufficiently related to a government interest, it will survive an equal protection challenge. In re Sandra H., 150 N.H. 634, 638 (2004). In this case, the Plaintiff is the motivating force behind the vehicle stopping with a green light; the vehicle only stopped because the Plaintiff solicited it to do so. Additionally, the Plaintiff was a pedestrian; the other party was the driver of a two-ton automobile in motion; it can't be said that theses two parties were similarly situated. As to the qualified immunity defense as applied to Officer Brandreth, unless the Plaintiff can demonstrate that it was clearly established law that Officer Brandreth had to chase down and ticket the Cadillac before he could ticket Ms. Petrello, then qualified immunity should apply on this basis as well to the Equal protection claim.

heading: C.  There was no violation of the Fourth Amendment in a brief stop to issue the Plaintiff a ticket.
content:
What should be clear from the Complaint was the Plaintiff was not arrested.  She was a pedestrian.  The officer came up to her, explained that she could not cause obstructions to traffic where there is a green light and she is causing a vehicle to stop, and issued her a "ticket."  The statute that the Plaintiff was cited under was RSA 644:2(II)(c), which provides that a person is guilty of disorderly conduct if:
"II.  He or she:
(c) Obstructs vehicular or pedestrian traffic on any public street or sidewalk or the entrance to any public building."
A police stop only becomes unreasonable if the time needed to handle the matter exceeds what is reasonable.  A seizure justified only by a police observed traffic violation becomes unlawful if it is prolonged beyond the time reasonably required to complete the mission of issuing a ticket for the violation. Rodriguez v. United States, 135 S.Ct. 1609, 1612 (2015).  The Plaintiff was never arrested in this case.  All that occurred was a temporary detention or a seizure. Where the officer has a reasonable concern about potential criminal activity based on his on the spot observations, and where immediate action is required to ensure that any criminal activity is stopped or prevented, the officer may stop the subject.  All that is required for such a stop is a belief that the circumstances gave rise to a reasonable suspicion of criminal activity. Schubert v. City of Springfield, 589 F.3d 496, 502 (1st Cir. 2009).  As the Plaintiff alleges in her Complaint, with citation to Officer Brandreth's police report which is attached to Exhibit C to the Complaint, "during a green light cycle for vehicles traveling north on Maple Street a black Cadillac came to a complete stop and handed [Ms. Petrello] something.  The vehicle then traveled north through the intersection.  The vehicle behind it . . . had to stop because the Cadillac stopped.  The light turned red and the Cherokee was unable to make it through on the green light cycle and would not have had to wait for the next light cycle." ¶23. The Plaintiff further alleges that during the interaction Officer Brandreth, "told Ms. Petrello that she could not stop vehicles." ¶24. The Plaintiff then alleges that Officer Brandreth, issued Ms. Petrello a summons to appear in Manchester District Court on July 9, 2015 for one count of disorderly conduct for obstructing vehicular traffic under RSA 644:2(II)(c). ¶25. The allegation is that there was a brief conversation between she and Officer Brandreth and she was issued a ticket to appear in court.  Further, the allegation is that Ms. Petrello was attempting to get vehicles to stop, that was her purpose on the sidewalk, and that a vehicle in fact stopped, even though it had the green light, causing another vehicle to stop behind it even though traffic had the right of way with the green light, and causing the second vehicle to miss the traffic cycle. The sole reason for the vehicle that obstructed traffic behind it to stop was Ms. Petrello's solicitation, and no other allegation is made as to any other reason why the vehicle would stop.  Accordingly under simple "but for" causation analysis, Ms. Petrello was causing an obstruction in traffic and therefore violated the disorderly conduct statute.  However, for immediate purposes here under a Fourth Amendment analysis, all that Officer Brandreth needed was a reasonable suspicion to stop Ms. Petrello because she was obstructing traffic, and that was satisfied.  Accordingly, there was no Fourth Amendment violation by Officer Brandreth.
In an analogous case, the Supreme Court of Washington found that application of a Washington ordinance that made it unlawful to intentionally obstruct vehicle traffic was constitutional and was not void for vagueness, and did not violate the Equal Protection Clause when a panhandler brought a challenge to it (for what was apparently obstruction of pedestrian as opposed to vehicular traffic).  A key factor in the decision was that the obstructing activity was intentional. Seattle v. Webster, 802 P.2d 1334 (1990).

heading: 1.  To the extent that plaintiff alleges the charge violated the Fourth Amendment, there was probable cause.
content: Plaintiff's Complaint is vague on this point in Count I as to what Officer Brandreth did to violate the Plaintiff's Fourth Amendment rights, but to the extent the claim is that the charge violated the Fourth Amendment, there was probable cause for the charge.  Probable cause exists when the circumstance is viewed from the vantage point of a prudent, reasonable, cautious police officer guided by experience and training are sufficient to warrant a reasonable person to believe that the individual had committed or was committing a crime. Estrada v. Rhode Island, 594 F.3d 56, 65 (1st Cir. 2010).  As Officer Brandreth was an eyewitness to the Plaintiff's actions in causing the car to stop so that she could obtain money from the driver who had a green light, thereby obstructing the traffic behind the solicited vehicle, the elements of probable cause under RSA 644:2(II)(c) were established. (For qualified immunity to apply, probable cause only had to be "arguable." See, Moses v. Mele, 711 F.3d 213, 216 (1st Cir. 2013).)

heading: A.  Motion to Dismiss For Failure To Join An Indispensable Party
B. Motions to Dismiss for Failure to State a Claim Upon Which Relief Can Be Granted
content: When considering a Rule 12(b)(6) motion, the court must accept the plaintiff's factual allegations as true and draw all reasonable inferences in the plaintiff's favor, but need not accept legal conclusions or unreasonable inferences.  Ashcroft v. Iqbal, 556 U.S. 662, 678, 129 S. Ct. 1937, 173 L. Ed. 2d 868 (2009); E.I. du Pont de Nemours & Co. v. Kolon Indus., 637 F.3d 435, 440 (4th Cir.2011). "To survive a motion to dismiss, a complaint must contain sufficient factual matter, accepted as true, to state a claim to relief that is plausible on its face." Iqbal, 556 U.S. at 678 (quoting Bell Atl. Corp. v. Twombly, 550 U.S. 544, 570, 127 S. Ct. 1955, 167 L. Ed. 2d 929 (2007)). "Threadbare recitals of the elements of a cause of action, supported by mere conclusory statements, do not suffice." Id.; Twombly, 550 U.S. at 555.  "Facts pled that are 'merely consistent with' liability are not sufficient." A Soc'y Without a Name v. Virginia, 655 F.3d 342, 346 (4th Cir.) (quoting Iqbal, 556 U.S. at 678).

heading: A.  The Complaint Should Be Dismissed For Failure to Join An Indispensable Party
content:
Justrite is a necessary party to this action because it is a real party in interest and permitting this suit to continue in its absence almost certainly will subject the Sofield Parties to conflicting legal obligations and an unnecessary multiplicity of lawsuits.  The funds at issue in this case do not belong to U.S. Bank, and U.S. Bank "does not have a stake in vindicating the alleged rights" of the real parties in interest, Justrite and the Sofield Parties.  Berkeley Acquisitions, LLC v. Mallow, Konstam & Hager, P.C., 262 F.R.D. 269 (S.D.N.Y. 2009). "Merely stakeholders or escrow agents which are not subject to liability in the lawsuit are not real parties to the action . . . "  Id., 262 F.R.D. at 273 (dismissing action brought by escrow agent for failure to join two of the real parties in interest to the transaction at issue).
Further, this Court will have to interpret the Escrow Agreement and the Purchase Agreement in order to resolve any such dispute as there is between the Sofield Parties and U.S. Bank; yet these same interpretations will need to be made by a court resolving the dispute that presumably will follow - regardless of the outcome of this lawsuit -- between the Sofield Parties and Justrite.  An increased potential for inconsistent judgments is grounds for finding a party necessary under Rule 19(a).  See Owens-Illinois, Inc. v. Meade, 186 F.3d 435, 441-442 (4th Cir.
1999); Teamsters Local Union No. 171 v. Keal Driveaway Co., 173 F.3d 915 (4th Cir. 1999); Schlumberger Indus., Inc. v. National Sur. Corp., 36 F.3d 1274, 1286 (4th Cir. 1994).
Thus, Justrite is a "necessary" party and should be joined in this action if feasible.  Of course, it would be proper for this Court to order U.S. Bank to join Justrite in this suit if such is feasible.  In the event Justrite cannot be joined, however, the Court must consider whether Justrite is an "indispensable" party so that this action must be dismissed.
As a party to the contracts in dispute in this action and the only party other than the Sofield Parties with a real interest in the hundreds of thousands of dollars at issue, Justrite is both a necessary and indispensable party.  See Berkeley Acquisitions, LLC, supra, 262 F.R.D. at 273 (finding that the other parties to a contract were indispensable in an action on one party's claims to money held in escrow, and quoting Crouse-Hinds Co. v. InterNorth, Inc., 634 F.2d 690, 701 (2d Cir. 1980) ("No procedural principle is more deeply imbedded in the common law than that, in an action to set aside a lease or a contract, all parties who may be affected by the determination of the action are indispensable.")
Resolution of U.S. Bank's claims will require the Court to determine the rights of U.S. Bank, Justrite, and the Sofield Parties under the Escrow Agreement and the Purchase Agreement. For example, the Sofield Parties will defend against U.S. Bank's claims on the merits on grounds that U.S. Bank did not distribute the escrowed funds to them either "inadvertently" or improperly, but in fact properly distributed them because Justrite's purported "Pending Claim Notice" was patently deficient and ineffective on its face under the terms of the Escrow Agreement. 4  Accordingly, U.S. Bank was required to make the final distribution pursuant to §5.3 of the Escrow Agreement.
The Sofield Parties will also defend U.S. Bank's claims on the merits on grounds that nothing in the Escrow Agreement obliged them to return any monies once such were distributed to them; that the Escrow Agreement terminated of its own terms once the final distribution was made; 5 that U.S. Bank has no obligation to seek return of the distributed funds and is proceeding as a mere volunteer in this lawsuit; 6 and that the Purchase Agreement specifically contemplates and provides that Justrite is to seek recourse for any such indemnification claim as it purports to have directly against the Sofield Companies since there are no longer any funds in escrow. 7
These same or similar arguments will be made in any litigation subsequently brought by Justrite (whether against the Sofield Parties and/or U.S. Bank) to dispute the right of the Sofield Parties to the final distribution of the escrowed funds and to assert its purported indemnification claim.  And if Justrite is not joined as a party in this action, Justrite will be entitled to re-litigate any determination made on these issues by this Court in this action.  The Sofield Parties will thus be exposed to multiple and potentially inconsistent judicial determinations on the same issues.
If the Sofield Parties prevail in this case, Justrite is still free to pursue them directly in another lawsuit on claims that the Sofield Parties must return the final escrowed amounts to U.S. Bank for escrow and that they are responsible to indemnify Justrite for the purported I-9 documentation issues.  If U.S. Bank prevails on its claims, it will subsequently have to bring an interpleader action, and the Sofield Parties will have to litigate their right to the escrowed funds again.  Either way, the Sofield Parties will be subject to multiple lawsuits regarding the same fundamental issues, imposing upon it the substantial risk of inconsistent judgments and unnecessary litigation.
Further, there is no suggestion that Justrite (and U.S. Bank, to the extent it is found to have any real interest in this dispute) would not have an adequate remedy by proceeding in the North Carolina state courts.  Justrite is apparently engaged in operations in North Carolina, as it purchased the Sofield Parties' business operations in the state, and can easily litigate in the state courts.  Most if not all of the witnesses and documents that would be pertinent to the dispute between Justrite and the Sofield Parties are located in North Carolina, and the state court is fully capable of rendering a fair decision among these North Carolina residents.  See Owens-Illinois, Inc. v. Meade, 186 F.3d 435, 441-442 (4th Cir. 1999) ("[W]e see no reason why the Circuit Court of Kanawha County, West Virginia will not provide an adequate remedy for the parties in this case. In fact, it is likely the best place for the adjudication of this matter since all of the Plaintiffs work at the same location and will share many witnesses and exhibits in the event a trial is held.  The West Virginia state court is more than capable of rendering an adequate and fair judgment in this matter.")
In sum, Justrite should be determined an "indispensable' party under Rule 19(b) and, unless U.S. Bank can join Justrite as a party, this action should be dismissed.

heading: 1.  Plaintiff Cannot State a Valid Claim for Conversion
content:
"There are . . . two essential elements of a conversion claim: ownership in the plaintiff and wrongful possession or conversion by the defendant. Variety Wholesalers, Inc. v. Salem Logistics Traffic Servs., LLC, 365 N.C. 520, 523, 723 S.E.2d 744, 747 (N.C. 2012); see also Gadson v. Toney, 69 N.C. App. 244, 246, 316 S.E.2d 320, 321-322 (N.C. Ct. App. 1984) ("To recover on a claim for conversion, plaintiff must prove both ownership in himself and the wrongful possession or conversion of the property by the defendant.") (citing Coulbourn v. Armstrong, 243 N.C. 663, 91 S.E. 2d 912 (1956)).
U.S. Bank does not allege that it owns the funds that it distributed from escrow to the Sofield Parties that are at issue in this action.  To the contrary, it alleges that it was an escrow agent with respect to such funds, which by definition means it had no ownership interest in them. Accordingly, U.S. Bank has not and cannot assert a claim for conversion.

heading: 2. Plaintiff Cannot State a Valid Claim for Unjust Enrichment
content:
In order to establish a claim for unjust enrichment, a plaintiff must allege: (1) it conferred a measurable benefit on the other party; (2) that party consciously accepted the benefit, and (3) the benefit was not conferred officiously or gratuitously. Booe v. Shadrick, 322 N.C. 567, 369 S.E.2d 554, 556 (N.C. 1988); Primerica Life Ins. Co. v. James Massengill & Sons Const. Co., 211 N.C. App. 252, 712 S.E.2d 670, 677 (N.C. App. 2011). Further, "a claim for unjust enrichment may not be brought in the face of an express contractual relationship between the parties." Madison River Mgmt. Co. v. Bus. Mgmt. Software Corp., 351 F. Supp. 2d 436, 446 (M.D.N.C. 2005) (citing Se. Shelter Corp. v. BTU, Inc., 154 N.C. App. 321, 572 S.E.2d 200, 206 (N.C. App. 2002)).
Here, the Escrow Agreement governs the relationship between U.S. Bank and the Sofield Parties.  Accordingly, U.S. Bank may not maintain a claim for unjust enrichment under North Carolina law.
Even if the claim were not barred in light of the Escrow Agreement, U.S. Bank's claim for unjust enrichment would fail.  "Not every enrichment of one by the voluntary act of another is unjust. 'Where a person has officiously conferred a benefit upon another, the other is enriched but is not considered to be unjustly enriched. The recipient of a benefit voluntarily bestowed without solicitation or inducement is not liable for their value.'"  Wright v. Wright, 305 N.C. 345, 350, 289 S.E.2d 347, 351 (N.C. 1982) (quoting Rhyne v. Sheppard, 224 N.C. 734, 737, 32 S.E. 2d 316, 318 (1944).
The complaint makes clear that in this case, the Sofield Parties did not solicit or induce U.S. Bank to distribute the remaining escrow funds to them.  U.S. Bank "officiously" distributed the funds to the Sofield Parties wholly on its own instance.  Further, U.S. Bank did not distribute any "benefit" that it owned and for which it could be entitled to compensation; it acted merely as an escrow agent distributing money rightfully belonging to another.  U.S. Bank fails to state a valid claim for unjust enrichment.

heading: 3.  Plaintiff Has Not Alleged Facts Sufficient To Establish an "Actual Controversy" As to Which This Court Properly Could Issue a Declaratory Judgment
content:
Finally, U.S. Bank requests a "declaratory judgment" with respect to the parties "respective rights and duties," by which it presumably means the parties' respective rights and duties under the Escrow Agreement and Purchase Agreement.  U.S. Bank's allegations do not establish an "actual controversy" between these parties as to which a declaratory judgment could properly be issued. 8
"[A] federal court may properly exercise jurisdiction in a declaratory judgment proceeding when three essentials are met: (1) the complaint alleges an 'actual controversy' between the parties 'of sufficient immediacy and reality to warrant issuance of a declaratory judgment;' (2) the court possesses an independent basis for jurisdiction over the parties (e.g., federal question or diversity jurisdiction); 9 and (3) the court does not abuse its discretion in its exercise of jurisdiction."  Volvo Constr. Equip. N. Am., Inc. v. CLM Equip. Co., 386 F.3d 581, 593 (4th Cir. 2004).  An "actual controversy" may exist where a plaintiff seeks a declaratory judgment in order to avoid the accrual of "avoidable damages."  See id. (citing NUCOR Corp. v. Aceros Y Maquilas de Occidente, 28 F.3d 572, 577 (7th Cir. 1994)). U.S. Bank fails to make any allegations identifying the potential liability or damage that it seeks to avoid that would entitle it to a declaratory judgment.  Nor do its allegations show how such a judgment entered by this Court as between the existing parties - U.S. Bank and the Sofield Parties - could provide it with relief with respect to such potential liability or damage.
The complaint and the exhibits attached to the complaint make clear that the Sofield Parties have no grounds to sue U.S. Bank and have never threatened litigation against U.S.
Bank.  Thus, there is no potential liability or damages claimed by the Sofield Parties that U.S. Bank seeks to avoid or have clarified.
Any liability that U.S. Bank might seek to avoid in this lawsuit would be a liability not to the Sofield Parties but to Justrite.  Yet U.S. Bank fails to allege any facts concerning any possible litigation by Justrite against it - much less establish that such litigation "appears to be unavoidable."  Moreover, even if litigation was threatened by Justrite, any potential liability of U.S. Bank to Justrite is both speculative and remote. 10  Further, the action taken by U.S. Bank that could give rise to liability (the release of the escrowed funds) has already occurred and could not occur again, so as lead to the accrual of additional damages, as U.S. Bank no longer holds any escrowed funds. 11
In any event, and more to the point, any determination by this Court as to whether (i) U.S. Bank had any right or obligation to withhold escrowed funds, and (ii) the Sofield Parties have any obligation to return funds already distributed to them will not have any binding effect upon Justrite, as it is not a party to this lawsuit and could not be bound by the Court's determinations.  Thus, any declaratory judgment by this Court is likely to amount to a mere advisory opinion, having no binding effect on Justrite in any subsequent suit it brings against either U.S. Bank or the Sofield Parties, except insofar as the Court's decision suits Justrite's purposes and is later used by it against either of those parties.  In effect, U.S. Bank and Justrite would get to take two bites at the same apple against the Sofield Parties.  For the Sofield Parties, on the other hand, this action would bring neither certainty nor finality, but only the expense of duplicative litigation and the risk of inconsistent legal determinations.
In sum, there is no "actual controversy" between U.S. Bank and the Sofield Parties that threatens U.S. Bank with the accrual of avoidable damages.  Any damages or liability of U.S. Bank would be as the result of a controversy between it and Justrite, and is both wholly speculative and not properly determined in this action, where Justrite has not been joined as a party.  Under these circumstances, a declaratory judgment is not proper in any event.
WHEREFORE, Defendants respectfully request that the Court grant their Motion to Dismiss and DISMISS Plaintiff's Complaint.

heading: B. Count I: "Violation of RESPA" Claim Should be Dismissed
content:
The request for information sent to BANA by Plaintiff does not constitute a proper QWR; thus, Plaintiff's claim should be dismissed.  To the extent the Court deems Plaintiff's request to be sufficient, BANA timely acknowledged and responded to Plaintiff's request.  [See Exhibit I and J to Plaintiff's Complaint, ¶¶ 48 and 49 of Plaintiff's Complaint, and Exhibit 1 to this Motion].
To constitute a proper QWR, the writing must "include a statement of the reasons for the belief of the borrower, to the extent applicable, that the account is in error or provides sufficient detail to the servicer regarding other information sought by the borrower." 12 U.S.C. § 2605(e)(1)(B).  Letters that "merely dispute a debt or request information are not 'qualified written requests,' and do not trigger the obligations under section 2605." Catalan v. GMAC Mort. Corp., 629 F.3d 676, 686 (7th Cir. 2011) (internal citations omitted). Here, the letter sent by Plaintiff, merely states that he "make(s) this request, based on our dispute of the amounts due and owing stated on/by your Complaint."  The letter goes on to list 13 categories of documents it would like to review.  This type of request is not sufficient to constitute a QWR as it merely disputes the debt and does not include a statement of the reason the borrower believes the account is in error, nor does it contain sufficient detail to allow BANA to review the account for potential errors in servicing. 12 U.S.C. § 2605(e)(1)(B); Catalan, 629 F.3d at 686.  Therefore, Plaintiff's claim that BANA violated RESPA fails and should be dismissed.
Even if this Court determines Plaintiff's letter constitutes a proper QWR, Plaintiff's claim still fails because BANA timely responded to Plaintiff's request, within 20 days of receipt of Plaintiff's letter, and this is within the appropriate time frame under 12 U.S.C. § 2605(e)(1)(A). Within 20 days of receiving a QWR, a servicer must send a written acknowledgement of the request. See 12 U.S.C. § 2605(e)(1)(A). Within 60 days after receiving a qualified written request, the servicer must, among other options, investigate the borrower's account and either provide the requested information or provide an explanation as to why the requested information is unavailable. See 12 U.S.C. §2605(e)(2)(C).  Here, Plaintiff admits that the October 4, 2011, letter sent by Blank Rome, LLP, on BANA's behalf is responsive to the alleged QWR request, but seems to suggest that the response was not timely sent.  [See ¶49 of Plaintiff's Complaint]. Plaintiff's allegations are misleading; he alleges that the QWR was sent to BANA on June 21, 2011, however Plaintiff's allegation is betrayed by Plaintiff's own exhibit.  [See Exhibit I to Plaintiff's Complaint].  The last page of Plaintiff's Exhibit I shows that Plaintiff did not sign the letter until July 5, 2011, not June 21, 2011, as stated in the Complaint.  [Id.].  Additionally, both BANA's acknowledgment letter and response letter indicate the QWR was received on July 11, 2011.  [See Exhibit I to Plaintiff's Complaint and Exhibit 1 to this Motion].  Thus the response, to the extent this was a valid QWR request in the first place, which it was not, was timely returned.
Pursuant to 12 U.S.C. 2605(a)(1)(A) and (2), the calculation of time excludes "legal public holidays, Saturdays and Sundays."  BANA's acknowledgement and response were both sent within the time allowed: the acknowledgement letter was sent nine days after receiving the QWR and the response letter was sent 60 days after receiving the QWR (excluding Labor Day, and all Saturdays and Sundays).  Plaintiff's claim should be dismissed for failing to state a claim against BANA.

heading: C. Count II: "Violation of the Indiana Home Loan Practices Act" Should be Dismissed for Failure to State a Claim
content:
Count II fails to meet the federal pleading standards under Fed. R. Civ. P. 8 and Rule 9(b), and therefore should be dismissed.  The Indiana Home Loan Practices Act prohibits persons from engaging in deceptive acts in connection with mortgage transactions.  I.C. § 24-9-3-7(c)(3). To establish a "deceptive act" Plaintiff must show that as part of a mortgage transaction BANA knowingly or intentionally: (1) made a material misrepresentation; or (2) concealed material information regarding the terms or conditions of the transaction.  I.C. § 24-9-2-7; Collins v. America's Servicing Company, 652 F.3d 711, 715 (7th Cir. 2011).  "Knowingly" means having actual knowledge at the time of the transaction.  I.C. § 24-9-2-7.
Merely reciting the elements of a cause of action without factual support, is not sufficient to state a claim.  Fed. R. Civ. P. 8.  To plead a cause of action demands more than an unadorned, "the-defendant-unlawfully-harmed-me accusation" or a "sheer possibility that a defendant has acted unlawfully." Iqbal, 129 S.Ct. at 1949 (citing Twombly, 550 U.S. at 555-56).  It "requires more than labels and conclusions, and a formulaic recitation of the elements of a cause of action will not do." Id. at 1954 (Rule 8 does not empower a defendant to plead the bare elements of a cause of action, affix the label "general allegation" and expect the complaint to survive a motion to dismiss), (citing Twombly, 550 U.S. at 555). Here, Plaintiff has failed to plead any facts to support his claim that BANA knowingly or intentionally made a material representation or concealed material information regarding the terms or conditions of his transaction, and instead merely concludes that BANA has done so.
Additionally, Plaintiff's claim under the IHLPA amounts to nothing more than allegations of misrepresentation or fraud; therefore, Plaintiff's claim must be pleaded with specificity. Fed. R. Civ. P. 9(b); Sears v. Likens, 912 F.2d 889, 893 (7th Cir. 1990) (ruling that officers failed to allege fraud with sufficient particularity where they neglected to "state in any detail what misrepresentations were made by the defendant, to whom these misrepresentations were made, when these misrepresentations were made, or how these misrepresentations furthered the alleged fraudulent scheme."); see also DiLeo v. Ernst & Young, 901 F.2d 624 (7th Cir.1990). In other words, Rule 9(b) requires the plaintiff to include "the 'who, what, when, and where' of the alleged fraud." Uni Quality, Inc. v. Infotronx, Inc., 974 F.2d 918, 923 (7th Cir.1992).  Here, Plaintiff fails to identify who made the alleged material misrepresentations, when, where, and about what.  Plaintiff merely states that "[t]hroughout [BANA]'s interactions with [Plaintiff], [BANA] engaged in one or more deceptive acts...with respect to [Plaintiff]'s home loan."  [See ¶ 60 of Plaintiff's Complaint].  Such a general allegation is utterly insufficient to inform the Court or BANA of what alleged acts constitute a knowing or intentional material misrepresentation under the Indiana Home Loan Practices Act. I.C. § 24-9-2-7.
Moreover, to the extent Plaintiff claims BANA engaged in a deceptive act in relation to the May 28, 2009, conditional loan modification offer, Plaintiff cannot establish that BANA knowingly or intentionally made a material misrepresentation or concealed information, because the plain language of the conditional loan modification offer sets forth all requirements to perform and the consequences of not performing. Collins supra, 652 F3d. at 715.  The conditional loan modification offer required that the agreement be returned, signed and notarized, as well as the bankruptcy stay be lifted prior to June 11, 2009, and payments be made on the first of each month.  [See Exhibit C to Plaintiff's Complaint].  The conditional loan modification offer also expressly states that "[i]n the event you do not or cannot fulfill ALL of the terms and conditions of this letter no later than June 11, 2009, we will continue our collections actions without giving you additional notices or response periods."  [See Exhibit C to Plaintiff's Complaint].
Plaintiff's own rendition of the facts indicates he violated nearly every condition-he does not allege that he signed and returned the loan modification offer to BANA, and he states that he did not make the first payment by the deadline of July 1, 2009, but rather made his first payment nine months later on April 14, 2010.  [See ¶¶22 and 25 of Plaintiff's Complaint]. Plaintiff alleges however, that BANA received a payment on July 6, 2009, which even if this payment was made by Plaintiff, this late payment violated the terms.  Plaintiff also indicates there was no Bankruptcy related activity until October 2009, when the lifting of the stay needed to happen before June 11, 2009.  [See ¶¶ 20-25 of Plaintiff's Complaint and Exhibit C to Plaintiff's Complaint].
Any allegation that BANA's collection actions constitute deceptive acts fails, as the conditional loan modification agreement specifically allows BANA to continue with collection actions, including foreclosure, in the event Plaintiff "do[es] not or cannot fulfill ALL of the terms and conditions of the [conditional loan modification offer]". Collins, 652 F3d. at 715; See Baker v. America's Mortgage Servicing, Inc., 58 F.3d 321, 328 (7th Cir.1995) (assessment of late fees under a mortgage agreement does not violate a state's consumer fraud statute if they are assessed in accordance with the express terms of the contract).  Therefore, Count II of Plaintiff's claim should be dismissed.

heading: D. Count III and V:  "Breach of Contract / Promissory Estoppel" and "Estoppel" Should be Dismissed for Failure to State a Claim
content:
i. Breach of Contract
Count III of Plaintiff's Complaint fails to state a claim for breach of contract.  As a preliminary matter, it is well-established that a plaintiff cannot succeed on a breach of contract claim unless he demonstrates his own performance of the contract's requirements. See Hukic v. Aurora Loan Services, 588 F.3d 420, 433 (7th Cir.2009).  Here, Plaintiff failed to perform under the contract by his own admission, which is fatal to his claim.  The loan modification agreement states in ¶4 "[e]xcept as otherwise specifically provided in this Agreement, the Note and Security Instrument will remain unchanged, and the Borrower and Lender will be bound by, and comply with, all terms and provisions thereof, as amended by this Agreement."  [See Exhibit C to Plaintiff's Complaint].  Like the loan modification agreement, ¶3(A) of the original Note provides that payments are due on the first of each month.  Also like the loan modification agreement, no grace period is provided; in fact ¶7(B) of the Note acknowledges that Plaintiff is in default if the payment is not made on the first of the month.  [See Exhibit B of Plaintiff's Complaint].
Here, the first payment was due on July 1, 2009, and by Plaintiff's own admission, the first payment was not made on time.  [See ¶¶22 and 25 of Plaintiff's Complaint].  At best, Plaintiff pleads BANA's records show a payment was received on July 6, 2009.2  [See ¶25 of Plaintiff's Complaint].  Even if Plaintiff alleged he made the first payment on July 6, 2009, which he does not, he is in default.  [See ¶¶ 3(A) and 7(D) of Exhibit B, and Exhibit C to Plaintiff's Complaint].  Additionally, the conditional loan modification offer specifically required that the bankruptcy stay be lifted on or before June 11, 2009, for the agreement to take effect.  This did not occur until December 2009.  [See ¶22 of Plaintiff's Complaint].  The plain language of the conditional loan modification offer is clear, and Plaintiff failed to demonstrate he performed according to the terms of the conditional loan modification offer, thus Plaintiff's claim for breach of contract fails and should be dismissed. Hukic, 588 F.3d at 433.
ii. Promissory Estoppel
Counts III and V of Plaintiff's Complaint both assert a claim for promissory estoppel, however Plaintiff fails to state a claim.
